&lt;div class=&quot;article-intro&quot; id=&quot;article-intro-div&quot;&gt;
	People with learning disabilities in Northern Ireland who are bullied or harassed are unlikely to report it to police because they don&#39;t realise they have been a victim of crime, a new report has found.&lt;!--Related Videos--&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;article-content&quot;&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		The study which has been carried out by the Police Ombudsman&#39;s Office and the Northern Ireland Policing Board also found they have largely positive experiences of the police.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		The report which is aimed at helping to promote the rights of the most vulnerable groups in society is looking at the issues faced by people with learning disabilities when dealing with the police and policing organisations.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		It found while people had positive views of the PSNI many incidents of bullying and harassment are not reported because victims didn&#39;t realise that they had been a victim of crime, or were unwilling to report it.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		The report makes a total of 24 recommendations to help ensure organisations respond appropriately to the needs of vulnerable people and also to help combat disability hate crime.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&quot;Many people with learning difficulties suffer bullying and harassment, but all too often they suffer in silence&quot;, Police Ombudsman Al Hutchinson said.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&quot;This report is about helping to ensure that disability hate crime is reported and that the best procedures are in place for combating it. It&#39;s also about ensuring that people with learning disabilities are treated at all times with dignity, fairness, equality and respect.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		Chair of the Policing Board&#39;s Human Rights and Professional Standards Committee welcomes the report but says a number of areas that need to be improved.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&quot;People with learning disabilities have the same right to justice and great policing as anyone else&quot;, Conall McDevitt, said.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&quot;It is important that the PSNI and other criminal justice agencies plan to ensure that right is fully upheld.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&quot;As a board we want to ensure that policing is accessible to everyone in our community and delivers a good service. The findings from this Report will help us do that&quot;, he added.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		Maureen Piggot, the Director of Mencap believes this study is hugely important.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&quot;It is by listening to the views and experiences of people with a learning disability we can find out what changes are needed if the policing and criminal justice agencies are to deliver equal access to justice for all&quot;, she said.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&quot;We urge that the recommendations of the report are implemented as a matter of urgency so that people with a learning disability can access the extra support they need to enjoy the same rights as others in our society&quot;, she added.&lt;/p&gt;
